physicalObject: white and gray camouflage-patterned game controller
explanation: Bulky plastic shell (~250 g) and wide prong make the weight and moment of inertia far higher than the ~10 g, pencil-like virtual brush. Pinching one corner gives a badly unbalanced feel.

physicalObject: black hard-shell suitcase with top handle

explanation: Pot is ceramic and unmoving; ribs supply texture but not the required 2 cm spring travel.
Top cap depresses slightly (<5 mm) with spring, but only one button exists and depth is far short of 2 cm.
Bristles compress about 5–8 mm with elastic feel, yet there is no discrete key travel nor stable bottom-out sensation.

physicalObject: blue Arduino Uno circuit board (header pins)
explanation: Pins are rigid; pressing produces no movement or springback, and surface is uncomfortable for repetitive tapping.
Foam cushion compresses ~2 cm and rebounds slowly, but area is continuous and lacks discrete, repeatable key mechanisms.
Trigger offers spring-loaded motion (~1–1.5 cm) and bottom-out feel, but only one actuator is available and width is minimal.
Pressing the rope merely squishes fibers without predictable depth or snappy return; nothing key-like is present.
Controller is a small, curved chassis ~15 cm wide with only a handful of clustered buttons; it lacks the 1 m lateral span and linear key arrangement of a piano.
Remote is long and flat, but only ~15 cm and narrow; button grid is too short to require two-hand reach or lateral arm shifts.
Two parallel sticks give a linear reference, but total reachable length is <30 cm and there are no discrete spring-back keys.
Small round base offers a single tap point; no horizontal strip or multi-key layout.
Curved fruit gives ~20 cm of tapping surface, but the form is soft, non-linear, and far shorter than the required 1 m span.
Horizontal arm provides a straight bar ~35–40 cm long—longer than most objects here—but still well under 1 m and lacks any moving key elements.
Mouse supplies only a single clickable area; no horizontal extension or distributed key field.
Soft, crinkly pouch roughly 25 cm across; provides broad but imprecise surface with no discrete key travel or spring response.
Small triangular object with no linear key layout or mechanical feedback; wholly mismatched.
Desk easily exceeds 1 m width, allowing full arm span; however it is a single rigid plane with no discrete keys or compliant travel, so only approximates spatial extent, not key mechanics.
Lid offers ridged horizontal surface ~55 cm wide—some cue for lateral motion—but still half the desired span and has no individual key displacement.
Front edge gives a straight line ~40 cm but is rigid and narrow; does not match key spacing or compliant travel.
Circular shape, small diameter, no linear extent or movable elements—provides none of the expected outline characteristics.
Short bar (~25 cm) with bulky ends; not wide enough and offers no key-like surface or travel.
Compact cylindrical pot—no resemblance to a 1 m horizontal keyboard outline.
Tall narrow cylinder provides only a single push point; shape and scale are incompatible.
Small handle (~17 cm) with bristle head; lacks sufficient span and any discrete key response.
Header pins give tiny discrete contact points, but board is only ~7 cm wide—nowhere near the 1 m keybed length.
Seat cushion spans roughly 1 m, providing correct lateral reach and allows both-hand placement; however surface is continuous and soft with no individual springy keys.
Tool offers only a pistol grip and a single trigger; outline and interaction drastically differ from a keyboard’s long keybed.
Irregular, bunched mass with no linear strip or separable key-like segments.
